Go to Colors -> Levels, which will bring up the levels dialog. Click on the "white point" eye-dropper (the rightmost of the three near the bottom right of the dialog). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0b/Levels_dialog_1_430.jpg/460px-Levels_dialog_1_430.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0b/Levels_dialog_1_430.jpg/759px-Levels_dialog_1_430.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":258,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":425.9340659340659,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fair_use">Fair Use</a> (screenshot)<br>
</p></div>"}

Click on the darkest part of the background that should be white, but isn't. Then hit "OK". {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/29/Levels_dialog_2_288.jpg/460px-Levels_dialog_2_288.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/29/Levels_dialog_2_288.jpg/760px-Levels_dialog_2_288.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":282,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":465.6043956043956,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fair_use">Fair Use</a> (screenshot)<br>
